    "body": "If moving js code to something more performant will improve performance, we probably should go this direction.\r\nBut I see several issues here.\r\n\r\nMoving some ui-related logic to backend may hinder testability. Ideally we should be able to run UI components (separated components, more complex views and event the whole app). Therefore the backend should be limited to do only network-related operations and expose data to frontend in a possibly simple form. Then it's easy to mock that backend. If backend contains UI logic, mocking backend requires duplicating that logic to have UI components working without real backend.\r\n\r\nSo if some operations should be rewritten to something faster than js, imo we should consider moving it to C++ and keep it as a part of UI, independent from the backend (which could be limited mainly to networking then). If for any reason it's more beneficial to keep that logic in GO (e.g. for sharing with mobile client), maybe we should consider creating separate library for that. That library could be used also in UI's testing environment, with no need of mocking of this part.\r\n\r\n@alexjba please let me know what you think about that. I'm not too much in the topic so I could easily miss something.",
